You have 15 HCP and a balanced hand with a strong five-card spade suit headed by the \S AKJ. What do you open?
[BID 1S] With 15 HCP and five spades to the \S AKJ, open one spade — your five-card major.
[BID 4S] Partner's jump to three spades showed about 10 to 11 points with three-card support, so with 15 HCP and a fine suit you have an easy game. Bid four spades.
[POST-AUCTION]
[show NS] Nine trumps and 24 combined HCP make four spades comfortable. The one worry is clubs: you hold \C AJT9 opposite the \C K, missing the queen. Rather than guess it, strip the side suits and throw RHO in — he has the queen and long hearts, so a forced lead gives you the suit.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
The plan is to dodge the club guess by an endplay. Draw trumps but leave one in dummy, cash your top side winners to strip RHO down, then put him on lead with nothing safe left — he must lead a club or concede a ruff-and-discard.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
Look at the clubs: \C AJT9 opposite the \C K, queen offside on your right. Don't finesse. Strip the diamonds, then exit and let RHO win; with only hearts and that bare club queen left, whatever he returns hands you the trick.
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \DJ. Top of your \D KJT interior sequence is a safe, attacking start that doesn't open a fresh suit for declarer.
[ROLE defender][STAGE post-lead]
You hold the club queen sitting over dummy's king. The danger is being thrown in late and forced to lead clubs, so take or set up your side tricks while you still have a safe exit.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Refusing the club finesse and letting RHO open the suit for you was the whole story — the strip did the work. Nicely played.
}
