You have 15 HCP and an unbalanced hand with a strong five-card spade suit and four clubs. What do you open?
[BID 1S] With 15 HCP and five spades to the \S AK, open one spade — your five-card major.
[BID 3C] Partner forced to game with two hearts, so you have room to describe your shape. Three clubs shows your four-card club side suit and lets partner picture the hand before he names the spade game.
[POST-AUCTION]
[show NS] An eight-card spade fit and 26 combined HCP put game out of reach of trouble. The lone guess is clubs — \C AJ87 opposite the \C K, queen missing. With the \H AK and short diamonds to strip, you can throw LHO in rather than finesse: he holds the queen and must lead a club back or give a ruff-and-discard.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
Aim to avoid the club guess. Draw trumps keeping a dummy entry, cash the \H AK and ruff a heart or two, strip the diamonds, then exit to LHO — out of safe cards, he opens clubs into your tenace or concedes a ruff-and-discard.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
The clubs are \C AJ87 opposite the \C K, queen on your left. Don't guess. Eliminate hearts and diamonds first, then put LHO on lead; whatever he returns, the club queen falls and you lose nothing in the suit.
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \H7. Three small hearts is a passive start; your \D AQ94 would only hand declarer a trick, so keep off it.
[ROLE defender][STAGE post-lead]
With three small clubs to the queen sitting under dummy's king, your job is to keep a safe exit. If declarer strips your hand and throws you in, you'll have to give the club suit away.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Stripping the rounded suits and endplaying LHO turned a 50-50 guess into a sure thing — that's the lesson in action. Well played.
}
